export const batch175 = {
  'the-wind-up-bird-chronicle.json': {
    base: { id: 'the-wind-up-bird-chronicle', title: 'The Wind-Up Bird Chronicle', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781635910988 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'Trouble arrives with a companion called change',
        text: 'Toru Okada had a wife and no job. He had left his seat at a law office where he had worked since college. The work paid the bills, but he wanted to try something else. He could afford to wait while looking for a new path, because Kumiko, his wife, brought home solid pay as a magazine editor and freelance artist.\n\nA few weeks passed and small fights began to break out at home. On one lazy afternoon, while doing housework, Toru picked up a strange phone call from a woman. The voice was teasing and vaguely sexual. Looking for something to take his mind off it, Toru walked out to search for their missing cat in a nearby empty lane, but he came back empty handed. After the cat vanished, Kumiko also slipped out one morning, leaving no note. Toru could not line up all that had just happened.\n\nSo begins a long search that pulls Toru in directions he never planned. Along the way he learns who Mr Honda was before people called him a spiritual reader. Lieutenant Mamiya, an old friend of Mr Honda from the war in Manchuria, tells a long story about Honda, and the conversation pulls Toru into the history of Japan in the second world war.\n\nIn the meantime, Toru keeps meeting odd characters whose lives quietly overlap. Nutmeg Akaska, one of these people, has a father who shares the curious mark on Toru cheek. People who have heard the call of the strange mechanical bird tend to meet sad ends.\n\nMystery draws the curious in. If you want people to leave you alone, leave nothing hidden. The reverse holds as well.\n\nIf you are wondering how the story ends, whether Toru finds the cat and his wife, keep reading. We will follow the bird together.',
        wordCount: 285
      },
      {
        title: 'A sweet marriage turned cold',
        text: 'Toru and Kumiko had been married for six years when he lost his job. With time on his hands, Toru took stock of his career and his marriage. He took the relationship apart in his mind, piece by piece.\n\nLife had seemed normal until that point, apart from the strange calls from a woman who asked for ten minutes of his time. The caller was Malta Kano. After some nudging from Kumiko, Toru agreed to meet her, and she turned out to be a psychic. Malta told him about a sister of hers called Creta, who claimed she had been assaulted by Noboru Wataya, Toru brother in law. Malta went on to say that Toru life was about to shift, and she pointed to the missing cat as the start of that shift.\n\nTangible details catch the eye but rarely amount to much. They are sideshows. The further you try to look, the broader the picture gets.\n\nThe Wataya family, Kumiko side, had a habit of consulting mediums and seers. The visit with Malta Kano brought Mr Honda back into Toru mind. Honda had been a spirit channeler whom Kumiko father had asked the couple to meet before the wedding. After meeting Malta, Toru noticed that both Honda and Malta had spoken to him about water. Honda had told him to be careful. Malta had spent years in austerities on the island of Malta, which gave her the first part of her name, and she had gone there to study water. Perhaps it was a coincidence, but both of them warned him about water, and the warning lodged in his chest.',
        wordCount: 263
      },
      {
        title: 'The story of May Kasahara and Creta Kano',
        text: 'A small grove of trees stood near the Okada house, and from it came a mechanical call that sounded like a bird winding a spring. The couple named it the wind-up bird, a label Kumiko had given it, and although they never saw the bird, they knew its sound well.\n\nWhile looking for the missing cat in the area, Toru met a teenage girl named May Kasahara who lived near some empty plots nearby. For a sixteen year old, Kasahara was a dark sort, always dragging every topic back to death. When Toru asked about a scar on her face and the way she limped, she told him about a motorcycle crash. She later admitted that the limp was a habit she had kept even after she had healed.\n\nA person company at any given moment often reflects where the heart sits.\n\nToru had a brush with death when Kasahara left him alone at the bottom of a dry well on the unused land where they often met. He had climbed down there to think about how low things had gone since Kumiko left. Kasahara later said sorry. Toru escaped in a way he could not explain, with help from Creta Kano.\n\nToru first met Creta in his own house. She had come at the request of her sister Malta to collect water samples from the Okada tap. During that visit, Creta told Toru a long story about her life. Their second meeting happened in a dream, and the dream was vivid. They made love in that dream more than once. What made it strange was that Creta later described how that encounter felt to her, in detail, when they next met. Toru could not place the moment. Was it a hallucination, or had it really happened?\n\nAccording to one detective agency, the large majority of people admit they would cheat if they knew they would never be caught.',
        wordCount: 311
      },
      {
        title: 'A close look at the day Kumiko walked out',
        text: 'Mr Honda, the old spiritual reader for the Okada family, died while Toru life was unraveling. When he came by to deliver a keepsake, Lieutenant Mamiya sat with Toru and told him long stories about the time he and Honda had spent at the front during the war. The keepsake came in a small box, and the Lieutenant told Toru to open it only after Honda had died. After the Lieutenant left, Toru found the box empty, and he sat staring at it for a long time.\n\nWar reshapes nations and reshapes the people and animals inside them.\n\nThe morning Kumiko left, there was no warning. While he was zipping up the back of her dress, Toru noticed she wore a new perfume. He asked about it kindly, and she left without a word, as though she was already late. Toru stayed up most of that night waiting for her to come home. She never did. The next morning he called her office and learned she had not shown up. She never did return, and Toru had Kasahara call the office days later to be sure.\n\nTrust in another person is one of the finest things we can hold on to, whether it pays off or not.\n\nToru later found the perfume case, a Christian Dior box, with a ribbon around it. It looked like a gift from a man. Interestingly, Kumiko had taken none of her clothes with her, not a single shoe or change of outfit. Toru would later learn she had stopped by the laundromat that morning to pick up a set of clothes he had dropped off.\n\nWhile Toru sat at home waiting for any word on Kumiko, Malta called and invited him to a meeting with Kumiko and Noboru Wataya. When the three of them sat down at the Shinagawa Pacific Hotel, Noboru claimed that his sister Kumiko had asked for a formal end to her marriage to Toru.',
        wordCount: 297
      },
      {
        title: 'Toru descent into darkness and Creta return',
        text: 'Toru took Mr Honda advice literally and went down into the deep, dry well on the unused land near his home. In the silence and the dark, he thought through his life. He tried to pin down the moment when things had begun to slip between him and Kumiko, and he landed on the day she went in for an abortion.\n\nWhen you need to climb, find the tallest tower. When you need to fall, find the deepest well and go all the way down.\n\nToru packed a bag, walked to the well, and lowered himself on a long rope ladder tied to a tree at the top. He brought only a bottle of water, and hunger found him quickly. He would have climbed back up the same way, but Kasahara, who had shown him the well in the first place, pulled up the ladder once he had passed out. She might have left him there. Creta woke him and lowered the ladder back down.\n\nWhen Toru came up, Creta was gone. He walked home, ate, washed up, and slept. Not long after, Malta called asking if he had seen her sister. Toru hurried back to the well and found Creta sitting at the bottom. She told him not to worry, she was there to think, just as he had been.\n\nTime alone sharpens the mind and loosens the hold of old feelings.\n\nToru went home and returned to the well the next morning. It was empty. While shaving the beard he had grown, he noticed a dark blue mark on his right cheek, the same cheek that grew warm during his long trances at the bottom of the well. Malta had asked him on her last call if he had noticed any change to his body.',
        wordCount: 270
      },
      {
        title: 'A turning point that changed the path',
        text: 'Toru realized he had not checked the mail since he came back from his time in the well. When he did, he found a letter in Kumiko handwriting. She tried to explain why she had left, her guilt over the affair, how she felt about the abortion years before, and a request that he stop looking for her.\n\nA single wrong step can change the shape of a calm future.\n\nHe went to bed that night shaken. In the morning he woke up to find a woman lying naked on Kumiko side of the bed. It was Creta. She picked up the story of her life where she had left off. Creta stayed for several days, wore Kumiko clothes, cooked for him, and they were together in the flesh, a replay of their dream. She invited him to come with her to Crete, the island she had always wanted to visit. Toru turned her down after talking it over with his uncle, Mr Tsuruta.\n\nMonths passed and Toru drifted. The Wataya family kept pressing him to sign the divorce papers, but he refused. He wanted to see Kumiko first. Their pressure grew into threats, and this went on for nearly a year. Around that time, Toru went back to the alley that led to the old Hanging House and found the lot had been torn down. Kasahara was nowhere to be seen.\n\nToru called his uncle and asked for the contact of the real estate agent who handled several plots in the Setagaya area. When he visited the agent, Mr Ichikawa, Toru asked what had happened to the plot where the Miyawaki family had lived. Ichikawa explained that a foreign investor had bought the land to flip it for a profit, but no one wanted it because of the dark history tied to the property.',
        wordCount: 285
      },
      {
        title: 'Coming back to the surface, a fresh start',
        text: 'Mr Ichikawa told Toru that the asking price for the land was about eighty million yen, given that no buyers had stepped up.\n\nA second thread came out of the call with his uncle. Toru needed to rebuild a normal life by paying attention to small things. Once he sat with that, he realized he had no one to talk to anymore. The Kasahara family had moved away. So Toru started to walk. At first he stuck to the blocks around Setagaya, then he took the train to Shinjuku Station and wandered. It was there that Nutmeg Akasaka first noticed him, and a friendship began. Nutmeg was not her real name, and her son name was not Cinnamon either.\n\nLife is what we make of the raw material it hands us, good or bad.\n\nNutmeg and Cinnamon noticed the mark on Toru right cheek. Nutmeg later told him her father had carried the same mark. As a sharp designer with expensive taste, Nutmeg gave Toru a complete style overhaul. Soon he was running a fitting service for wealthy middle-aged women.\n\nSpend cash on what money can buy. Spend time on what it cannot.\n\nNutmeg and Cinnamon bought the empty lot, built a small elegant house on it, and deepened the well even though it was still dry. They added a steel ladder. Toru came to the rebuilt property through the back alley of his own house. Only Cinnamon used the gated front. He drove a black Mercedes and brought his clients in through the same hidden way, so the neighbors had no idea who owned the place or what went on behind the tall walls. Toru spent nights in the well and days in the house, and went home now and then.',
        wordCount: 281
      },
      {
        title: 'Where imagination meets the real world',
        text: 'Through Mr Ushikawa, a quiet spy, Noboru Wataya learned that Toru was the new owner of the Hanging House. Noboru tried to bargain with Toru, offering to buy the property in return for a chance to speak with Kumiko. The aim was to protect his political standing. Noboru offered to clear the eighty million yen mortgage.\n\nMr Ushikawa then pitched Toru a deal to chat with Kumiko online through a computer. In time, Nutmeg and Cinnamon traced Noboru and Toru back to the speculative press about the Hanging House. They cut their ties to Toru and the lot without warning.\n\nToru stayed away from the property for six straight days. The sixth day, the silence drove him back. Knowing he might lose the place now that the fitting work had ended, he climbed down the well one last time. Down there, he slipped into a trance and found himself in the same room he had visited on his earlier trips.\n\nThe mind can shape what the hand eventually builds.\n\nIn that room, Toru met a woman who spoke with many voices, and one of them was Kumiko. Then a second figure appeared and lunged at Toru with a knife, leaving cuts on his left shoulder and right cheek. Toru fought back in the trance with a baseball bat and cracked open the attacker skull.\n\nWhen the trance cleared, Toru was back at the bottom of the well and the well was full of water. The cuts and the aches from the trance were still on his body. The water started to rise and Toru would have drowned if Cinnamon Akasaka had not pulled him out at the last moment.',
        wordCount: 277
      },
      {
        title: 'Final thoughts',
        text: 'Toru first blamed his troubles on quitting his job without a plan. His early meeting with Mr Honda had made him doubt anything that smelled of the supernatural.\n\nWhat had happened to Creta at the hands of Noboru Wataya echoed what later trapped Kumiko. The affairs Kumiko had before leaving her husband were clearly beyond her control. The same was true of Kumiko sister, who died young.\n\nAfter she left the Setagaya area, May Kasahara grew close to the wind-up bird man, Toru. Toru and Creta drifted apart over time, though Creta eventually moved to Japan, against her old wish to settle in Crete.\n\nToru time in the well, the mark on his cheek, and a chain of strange events all pushed him, slowly and without his noticing, toward Kumiko. In the end, his instincts had pulled him along the path he needed to walk to free Kumiko from her brother grip. The ending of the book feels open and quiet, but at least Toru held on to his life and his mind.\n\nMemories and thoughts age, just as people do. But some thoughts never get old and some memories never fade.\n\nToru was the only person who heard the dark call of the wind-up bird. No one ever saw the bird, and the story hints that those who hear it meet grim ends. So the bird stands for the strange trials each person carries and the lonely weight that comes with them.\n\nTry this. Look around at the people close to you today. Appreciate them for who they are. Try to understand them well enough that no outside voice can come between you.',
        wordCount: 291
      }
    ]
  },

  'the-wisdom-of-sundays.json': {
    base: { id: 'the-wisdom-of-sundays', title: 'The Wisdom of Sundays', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781608674457 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'What we know sets the edges of our world',
        text: 'What you believe about life shapes how you live. Your beliefs set the fence around what you experience. Knowledge is the bridge from one place in life to the next. Most of us know this, but a busy life often stops us from setting aside time to learn things that change us. That is why tools like the Headway app matter. With Headway, you can pick up the main ideas of a book in minutes. Super Soul Sunday is another example of a tool that helps people grow, one small step at a time.\n\nSuper Soul Sunday is a talk show that premiered in October 2011, hosted by Oprah Winfrey. It centers on long, heartfelt talks with spiritual teachers and thinkers from around the world. Oprah invites guests and asks them about awakening, purpose, the afterlife, and everything in between.\n\nYou get more joy from developing and sharing your gifts with the world than from anything else you do.\n\nIn The Wisdom of Sundays, Oprah gathers some of the richest moments from her guests. Those insights have been distilled into the chapters ahead. If you put these ideas into practice, this summary will help you rise toward the best version of yourself.\n\nIn the chapters that follow, you will learn why you are a spiritual being and why living from that place matters, why your thoughts carry more weight than your actions, how to find good in bad situations, how to use gratitude to pull more good into your life, and more.\n\nA small note worth knowing. The name Oprah on screen is not the name on her birth certificate. Her name there is Orpah, taken from a figure in the Old Testament book of Ruth. People kept getting it wrong, and the new spelling stuck.',
        wordCount: 282
      },
      {
        title: 'Live from the inside out',
        text: 'You are a spiritual being having a human experience. Your body and mind help you deal with the world around you, but they are not the real you.\n\nThe real you is precious and beautiful, and it lives on the inside. Your thoughts, the shape of your body, and every memory you carry are not the real you. Once you see this clearly, life starts to shift for the better.\n\nSince we are all spirits, it makes sense that we would live as spiritual people. Too many of us have not yet trained our spirits for the kind of life we are meant to live. The world we grew up in, and how fast it moves, often keeps us from that kind of training.\n\nStill, being spiritual is every person birthright, and it is the only path to a full life. Chasing things cannot fill the deeper hunger. They can meet needs, but the empty place inside us is meant to be filled by our spirits. So how do you fill it? Practice spiritual living, and the first step is self-awareness.\n\nBefore you set this aside, spirituality is not the same as religion. It does not matter if you are an atheist or part of one of the many faiths in the world. You are human first. Religion tries to help you become the highest version of yourself. Your religion does not decide if you are spiritual.\n\nWhat matters is that you go past your mind and into your soul, where wisdom and intuition live.\n\nSpirituality begins when you start to live from your soul outward, instead of just reacting to whatever happens around you.\n\nA daily practice of awareness is a strong start. Set aside time to meditate. Be more conscious and deliberate about everything you do, including the small things.',
        wordCount: 265
      },
      {
        title: 'Your intentions outrank your actions',
        text: 'Life runs on principles. When you know them, you can move through life with far less wasted effort. Without that knowledge, you keep pushing and getting little in return. It can wear you down.\n\nLearn the principles that run life. It will pay back many times over. One of the most important is the law of intention.\n\nDifferent teachers have put the law of intention into different words, so a version of it is probably familiar to you. In short, the energy you send out is the energy that comes back.\n\nUse the law of cause and effect by doing more of what produces the results you want.\n\nWhat you sow is what you reap. You can see this law play out in your own life, in the lives of people around you, and across the world. Think of the kindest person you know. Think of how much kindness flows back to them. That is the law of intention at work.\n\nIf you want more love, give more love. If you want to be treated well, treat others well.\n\nThe principle that rules my life is intention. Thought by thought, choice by choice, we are co-creating our lives based on the energy of our intention.\n\nThe law of intention runs deeper than your actions. You can perform a good deed while your heart is set on something else. In that case, you will not reap the reward of the deed. You will reap what your heart is sending out. Match your heart and your actions if you want the rewards you hope for.\n\nA small note worth knowing. Dentistry is one of the oldest jobs in the world, with roots going back thousands of years.',
        wordCount: 264
      },
      {
        title: 'Listen to your inner compass',
        text: 'A spiritual compass is built into each of us from birth. If you let it, this compass will guide you through the big and small decisions of life. Learn how to hear it, and you will spare yourself a great deal of pain.\n\nYou can call this compass your inner GPS or your intuition, which is the word most people use. It is an emotional guidance system that is always on. It cheers you on when you are on the right track and warns you when you are heading toward a crash.\n\nWhen you are confused and do not know what to do, trust your intuition.\n\nLet us try a real case. Suppose your marriage is in trouble and you are thinking about divorce, but you are torn because you want your children to grow up with both parents. In a case like this, do two things. First, give it some time, a few weeks or months, so you can calm down enough to hear your inner voice clearly. Second, pay close attention to your Self, spelled with a capital S. The Self here is not your personality. It is your soul.\n\nNotice how you really feel about the situation. Watch your feelings for a while and see if they stay steady. Steady feelings on a hard question are a strong sign that your Self is talking. You will never regret following that voice.\n\nYour life speaks to you in whispers, that little nudge that says something does not feel right. If you ignore those nudges, you will eventually take a hit that feels like a brick to the head.\n\nUse this habit any time you face a choice that will shape your life, such as a career move or a marriage.',
        wordCount: 263
      },
      {
        title: 'Life happens for you, not at you',
        text: 'When life hands you lemons, make lemonade. You have probably heard that line, but you may not know where it came from. The saying was first written down in 1915 by Christian anarchist writer Elbert Hubbard.\n\nThe phrase is a call to stay hopeful. It tells you not to sit still when life beats you down. Learn to fight back and turn a bad spot into a good one.\n\nDo not walk through life with a what will be, will be mindset. Go after what you want, without apology.\n\nWhen you want something, want it hard enough to go the distance for it.\n\nBut how do you keep going when failure and disappointment are bound to come? The answer is that you control your response. Hard things happen to everyone. What sets some people apart is how they respond to those hard things. Every event in life is neutral until you label it good or bad.\n\nDeath is one of the heaviest things a person can face. You can let it pull you under, or you can let it push you to grow. A growth mindset does not deny pain. It accepts what is true and grows through it.\n\nOprah puts it this way. Everything that comes to you is being drawn into your life as a way to help you grow into who you were meant to be. It is not the thing that matters. It is what that thing opens up inside you.\n\nDecide today not to let life flatten you. Push through every hard thing. You carry more strength than you know. Reach for it.',
        wordCount: 265
      },
      {
        title: 'Gratitude turns everything around',
        text: 'Anything you thank on a regular basis tends to keep showing up in your life. That is why great spiritual teachers keep pointing back to gratitude. The practice is powerful. It will pull fear and worry out of your daily life.\n\nGratitude will not erase every problem, but it can help you hold onto your peace in the middle of a hard season.\n\nGratitude lives on a scale inside all of us. Once you start the practice and keep it up, your thanks will reach into the smallest corners of your life.\n\nIf this is new to you, start with a gratitude journal. There are apps for it, but a simple notebook works just as well.\n\nFill in the journal before bed. Pick three things you were most grateful for that day and write them down. They can be tiny things. Keep going until the habit feels natural.\n\nThe result is more calm and a deeper sense of fullness.\n\nGratitude can transform any situation. It shifts your vibration and moves you from negative to positive.\n\nThe reason this practice works so well is that it is anchored on the creator, the universe, or whatever you believe in. Gratitude reminds you that you do not have to force things to happen. It opens your eyes to the truth that all things work together for your good, that the universe is lining up good things for you, and that your job is to get in the right place to receive them.',
        wordCount: 254
      },
      {
        title: 'Closing thoughts',
        text: 'Deep inside every one of us is a need to be seen, to belong to a circle of people who love us for who we are, and not for the labels society hands out or the ones we hand ourselves.\n\nSomehow we all know we are unique in ways no one else can copy. We want to live that truth without fear of being mocked or brushed off.\n\nThat need has driven many people into frustration, because trying to fit in rarely works. Is there a way out? Yes. Learn not to force things. Move through your life one step at a time. Follow the pulls of your own heart, and avoid doing things only to feel accepted. Know that timing matters. The universe is on your side even when it does not feel that way.\n\nYou have a unique calling. There is a circle of people waiting for what you carry. Not everyone will see your worth, but the ones it is meant for will. Most people only notice the seed of a calling after it has already begun to grow.\n\nThe ideas in this summary will help you find and grow your potential. Start with awareness, because it will help you learn about your true Self.\n\nIf you concentrate on what you do not have, you will never have enough. Be thankful for what you have and you will end up having more.\n\nTry this. Practice a simple daily mindfulness meditation. Pick a time of day that you can keep, and call it your meditation time. Sit down. Close your eyes and watch your thoughts. After a while, you can open your eyes and focus on your body sitting still, or on what is around you. Do this for ten to fifteen minutes each day.',
        wordCount: 275
      }
    ]
  },

  'the-xx-brain.json': {
    base: { id: 'the-xx-brain', title: 'The XX Brain', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781606949943 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'Female health is different and has been overlooked',
        text: 'There is no hiding that gender gaps exist all over the world. Those gaps show up in healthcare too. For most of history, medicine was run by men and shaped around male bodies. Earlier scientists thought the only real difference between men and women was the reproductive organs.\n\nThat idea was wrong, and it left modern medicine poorly equipped to help women. A clear example is the heart attack. The classic warning signs, like crushing pain in the chest and left arm, are mostly drawn from male patients. Women often show different signs, like sweating, nausea, and trouble breathing.\n\nAlzheimer disease is a good second example. The number of people with the disease is on track to triple by 2050, with about fifteen million in the United States alone. Two thirds of those patients are women. Women also do most of the caregiving for relatives with the disease. Yet Alzheimer is rarely treated as a women health issue.\n\nWomen are also diagnosed with depression and anxiety about twice as often as men.\n\nThe author offers practical steps that women can use to take charge of their health. The steps work for any gender and will lift your mood, improve sleep, lower stress, raise energy, and protect your brain.\n\nMen reading this will also find useful information. Whether you are curious about women health or have a female relative with Alzheimer or another cognitive disease, the science here will broaden your view. The point is not to put men and women against each other but to understand our differences and use them well.',
        wordCount: 244
      },
      {
        title: 'How male and female brains differ',
        text: 'Male DNA carries XY chromosomes and female DNA carries XX chromosomes, which gives the book its title. What fewer people know is that X chromosomes are larger than Y chromosomes and carry many more genes. Because genes drive hormone production, the female brain is shaped by hormones far more than the male brain is. Understanding those hormones helps women make better health choices and lower their risk of cognitive decline.\n\nEven with the work of modern researchers, medicine still struggles to address women needs. Most studies are done with men in mind. Over time, it has become clear that men and women respond to drugs differently during testing, which means a drug can work well for one sex and not the other.\n\nHormones drive most of the activity in the brain and the body, including metabolism, healing from injury, and tissue growth.\n\nThese biological differences do not dictate behavior. They cannot justify the social gaps between the genders. Those gaps come from how we live, not from biology. Some researchers have tried to argue that male brains are superior, but the fact that the wiring differs does not make one brain better than the other.\n\nEven though Alzheimer is a major threat to women, it gets little attention, and women themselves often miss the warning signs. Female complaints are still brushed off as bias or age. The disease is often treated as the unavoidable result of bad genes and old age. That is not true. Genes set the risk, but our environment, habits, stress, and sleep decide whether the disease shows up.\n\nWomen have entered careers that used to be closed to them. They have not traded roles with men. They have simply gained more responsibilities. Juggling work and home has hurt women health and shortened lives. The myth that women live much longer than men is fading. The gap has shrunk from about five years to almost nothing.',
        wordCount: 268
      },
      {
        title: 'Alzheimer risks and how to measure them',
        text: 'Some medical conditions raise the risk of Alzheimer or make it worse. These include diabetes, heart disease, obesity, and depression. Hormonal risks include thyroid disease, pregnancy, and menopause. It is important to keep a close watch on your health. One thing you can do today is measure your risk for obesity and heart disease. Check your body mass index, your waist to height ratio, and your blood pressure. Once you have the numbers, you can set goals like losing weight or lowering blood pressure, and both will lift your overall health.\n\nThere are also blood tests that measure your risk for diseases that hurt thinking. Check your thyroid, blood sugar, insulin, and cholesterol. Check homocysteine and your vitamin levels, especially omega 3s and B vitamins. Take cognitive tests that measure memory, thinking, and problem solving. Self tests online can be useful, but they are not a substitute for a medical exam. A neuropsychologist can give you a real evaluation.\n\nIf you cannot reach a doctor right away, start with online questionnaires on government health sites. They ask about your habits, age, gender, family history, and genetic background.\n\nThen look at your lifestyle and environment. Toxins, smoking, poor diet, and a sedentary life all add risk. The good news is that no matter what your DNA says, you can prevent many diseases by taking care of your body and your brain.\n\nThe key is prevention, and the field calls it precision medicine. Precision medicine looks at all the factors, including genes and environment, not just DNA. Female and male brains differ, so the prevention plan should be female specific. Precision medicine can build a plan that fits you.\n\nEvery woman is unique, and her risks and needs have to be mapped. What works for your friend may not work for you.',
        wordCount: 273
      },
      {
        title: 'How menopause and pregnancy shape women health',
        text: 'Studies show that menopause changes more than fertility. It reshapes the brain. Women going through menopause often report brain fog and memory lapses, along with hot flashes, night sweats, trouble sleeping, hormonal depression, stress, and lower sex drive. Hot flashes and night sweats show that the brain is struggling to manage body temperature. Menopause acts as a switch that weakens the female brain defense against Alzheimer and dementia, and that is when the disease takes hold. Since men do not go through menopause, their brains are better armed to fight these diseases later in life.\n\nMenopause reshuffles the neuroendocrine system and affects both brain and body. The trouble is that women are judged for the emotional and neurological symptoms that come with it, and that judgment keeps many women quiet. They worry about being dismissed or laughed at. So they never get the support they need.\n\nMenopause is the end of menstruation and is confirmed after twelve months without a period.\n\nBecause menopause can shape a woman life for decades and on its own raises Alzheimer risk, we need more research and better treatments right away.\n\nPregnancy brings another big hormonal shift. New mothers often notice a fog called momnesia, which is a playful name for forgetfulness after birth. Memory slips come from changes in the brain and from the constant demands of caring for a newborn.\n\nAbout one in ten women develop postpartum depression after giving birth. The condition brings anxiety, deep sadness, and a loss of self worth. It used to be hidden and ignored, but it is now recognized as a real illness that responds to treatment. The key is to see a doctor as soon as the symptoms show. Early treatment works best.\n\nA small note worth knowing. Mothers of newborns tend to lose about seven hundred hours of sleep during the first year of parenting.',
        wordCount: 288
      },
      {
        title: 'A healthy diet feeds a healthy brain',
        text: 'Nutrition is still not given the attention it deserves. Food keeps us alive, and once we break it down, it literally becomes part of us. The quality of our food shapes the health and strength of the brain, not to mention the body.\n\nFemale and male bodies also respond to food differently. Since most diet research has been done on men, the best diet for women is still not fully mapped. Diets that cut out whole food groups, like no fat or no carb plans, can be harmful because the body needs a range of nutrients.\n\nMen may be from Mars and women from Venus, but on Earth both benefit from eating well.\n\nThe Mediterranean diet is the only plan with solid science behind it for women. It feeds the body and the brain, lowers the risk of dementia, stroke, and breast cancer, and keeps the brain younger for longer compared with the Western diet. Mediterranean meals are high in fiber and use moderate amounts of mostly plant based fats. Western meals lean on saturated fats from animals. A Mediterranean plate might be seafood and artichokes drizzled with olive oil. A Western plate might be fried chicken with french fries.\n\nTry to eat the rainbow. Include fruits and vegetables of many colors.\n\nThe foods to eat every day include vegetables, fruits, whole grains, fish, full fat organic yogurt, kefir, nuts, and berries. Watch what you drink and how much. Too much alcohol or coffee can hurt the brain. A small glass of red wine now and then is fine, as are two small coffees a day or one espresso. Green tea is a healthy swap for coffee. And drink plenty of water, the simplest and most important drink for any person.',
        wordCount: 260
      },
      {
        title: 'Move your body',
        text: 'Exercise is a pillar of long term health. Studies show that regular exercise keeps the brain young, sharpens memory, slows the buildup of Alzheimer plaques, and reduces brain shrinkage. It lifts mood, lowers stress, and helps with weight. It also cuts the risk of heart disease, stroke, and diabetes. There is a lot to gain.\n\nCurrent research suggests that about sixty percent of adults get less than two and a half hours of physical activity a week. Women, in particular, get less exercise than men. The gap comes from history. Girls were not allowed to take physical education in school until 1823, and women still carry most of the child care at home, which leaves them less time to move.\n\nBodies differ in how they respond to exercise. Men tend to do well with short, hard bursts like jumping rope. Women tend to do better with longer, moderate sessions like aerobics. Women need to push hard enough to raise their heart rate and keep the routine steady to see results.\n\nTry a brisk twenty minute walk each day. Keep it regular or the benefit fades.\n\nBodies need rest as well as motion. It is well documented that time in nature restores energy, so go outside more often. Try meditation, acupuncture, yoga, or any other practice that calms you. Turning on airplane mode on your phone brings a quick sense of calm. Add plants to your home or office to make the space more peaceful.\n\nA small tip for parents. Teach your child simple breathing routines from an early age. Three deep breaths can settle a tantrum in minutes.\n\nWe cannot control every source of stress in our lives, but we can control how we respond to it.',
        wordCount: 260
      },
      {
        title: 'Closing thoughts',
        text: 'Even though modern medicine is still catching up on what women need, every woman can take steps today to keep her body and brain healthy. The first step is to reset priorities. Well being comes before outer beauty.\n\nWomen should care for their hormones. They go through major hormonal shifts across a lifetime, including the start of menstruation, pregnancy, and menopause. Mood swings, weight gain, and sadness during these shifts are normal and never something to be ashamed of. Women have every right to medical care that supports them through these phases. Knowing how the female body and brain work makes it easier to handle problems that come up.\n\nKeep a close watch on your health. Take simple steps like tracking your risk for major diseases, seeing your doctor on a regular schedule, and encouraging loved ones to do the same. A healthy family is a happy family.\n\nRegular exercise and a balanced diet build muscle and protect thinking. They lower the risk of Alzheimer, heart attack, stroke, and obesity, and they can add healthy years to your life. The care you put in now pays back for years to come.\n\nTry this. Write out a daily routine that fits your life. Include when you wake up and go to bed, what you eat, when you move, and how you spend time with others. Putting it on paper makes it easier to keep all those pieces in place. If a healthy diet is hard to maintain on your own, ask the people you live with to join you. If junk food is not in the fridge, you will not be tempted to reach for it.\n\nYou made it to the end. Nice work.',
        wordCount: 259
      }
    ]
  },

  'thinkertoys.json': {
    base: { id: 'thinkertoys', title: 'Thinkertoys', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781637536299 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'How pressure shapes people',
        text: 'Under stress, people act like one of two animals. Some freeze in place like a kitten and wait for rescue. Others, like a baby monkey, run toward a caregiver and hold on tight. The tools in this book help people who already have the monkey mindset, and they can also help kittens switch into a more active mode.\n\nYour creative edge comes from being active and positive about yourself.\n\nYour attitude is a choice you can make. We cannot choose our parents or the day we will die, but we can choose how to live between those two points. Creative people are not just acted upon. They choose to be the subject of their own lives. They pick I over me.\n\nThe tools in this summary will push you to see the world from a new angle. Where you once saw one path or none, you will start to see many.\n\nYou will look at the same information as everyone else and notice something new.\n\nMichael Michalko wrote this book to share his methods. The tools fall into two broad camps, linear and intuitive. Linear tools help you rework existing ideas into fresh angles. Intuitive tools tap your imagination to spark new ones.\n\nWhat does this knowledge give you? It helps you generate new ways to make money, design business solutions, improve existing ideas, become more valuable to the people around you, refresh old industries, and lift productivity.\n\nLearning the techniques is not enough. You have to use them. That is why you need the monkey mindset. If you are stuck in kitten mode, the rest of this book will show you how to switch. The techniques are simple and they work.',
        wordCount: 256
      },
      {
        title: 'Creative growth starts with killing self doubt',
        text: 'A creative mind has to push past fears, uncertainties, and doubts, or what the author calls FUDS. Admit your FUDS, name them, and let your mind look for replacements. The shift comes from two simple beliefs. You are capable of change. You are no less talented than anyone else.\n\nUse the tick tock exercise to take on your FUDS. Draw a table with two columns. Label the left tick and the right tock. Under tick, write the negative thought that feeds your doubt. Under tock, write a positive line that cancels out the negative.\n\nAfter reframing, follow up with self affirmation and creative affirmation. Self affirmation recalls your past wins and your good qualities to fuel new wins. Creative affirmation is the belief that you are creative. Once you see yourself as a winner, a thinker, and a solver, you will act like one.\n\nWrite your affirmations about being creative for five days in a row.\n\nSet an idea quota for yourself to move from a kitten to a monkey.\n\nAn idea quota is a simple exercise. Give yourself a target number of ideas to come up with every day.\n\nPay attention to the world around you. You will find things that push you toward new ground. Step away from your routine now and then to force new thinking. Feed your mind by reading and by thinking about what you read. Build a brain bank, a place to store ideas for later. Travel exposes you to new eyes and new insights. When an idea shows up, write it down right away. Listing ideas as they come sharpens your thinking. Flexible thinking comes from seeing beyond the conventional answer.\n\nNow that you have moved from kitten to monkey, how do the thinkertoys help you tinker with a problem until it gives way?\n\nA small note worth knowing. Thomas Edison held over a thousand patents in his lifetime.',
        wordCount: 272
      },
      {
        title: 'Turn problems into openings',
        text: 'Coming up with ideas without a clear target is a waste of effort. List the problems you want to solve. Ask what you gain by solving each one. The gain may be money, emotion, attitude, or skill. Otto Frederick Rohwedder, for example, spent sixteen years building a bread slicing machine because he did not enjoy slicing bread himself. He never got rich from it. His gain was the simple pleasure of pre sliced bread.\n\nOnce you are clear on the benefit, take the challenge and start generating ideas. The number of ideas you can put on the table sets the pace at which you reach a fresh answer. The tools you pick also depend on how you framed the problem.\n\nQuestions help you look at a problem from many sides until you find the real issue to tackle.\n\nYou can reframe a problem by swapping words for their synonyms or by writing questions that open the mind. Ask, for example, what new funding sources could support this project. Look at the problem up close and from a distance. Break it down into smaller pieces and tackle each one on its own.\n\nA small note worth knowing. By 1933, about eighty percent of bread sold in the United States came pre sliced.',
        wordCount: 184
      },
      {
        title: 'Use both sides of the brain for fresh solutions',
        text: 'A single point of view draws imaginary lines around the problem and kills fresh thinking. Each of us leans on one side of the brain more than the other, left or right.\n\nSingle points of view often come from ignoring the side of the brain you use less.\n\nLeft brained thinkers tend to follow steps and stick to what is in front of them. Right brained thinkers tend to see the whole picture and pull ideas out of thin air.\n\nStatisticians, researchers, and writers lean left. Musicians, composers, and other creatives lean right. The thinkertoys help you bring both sides online. Linear thinkertoys suit ordered or sequential problems. Intuitive thinkertoys suit big picture thinking or new lines of thought. To get the most from the tools, use one at a time, alternate between linear and intuitive, and pick the tool randomly when you face a fresh challenge.\n\nBut do not chase every idea the tools throw at you, or you will be pulled in too many directions. Collect and write down your ideas. Then judge them against a standard that fits the kind of suggestions on the table. The ideas that pass become possible solutions.\n\nIf you are ready to start, begin with the first set of linear thinkertoys.',
        wordCount: 195
      },
      {
        title: 'Rearrange the ideas you already have',
        text: 'The thinkertoys that help you see a challenge from a new angle include False Faces, Slice and Dice, Cherry Split, Think Bubbles, and Scamper.\n\nFalse Faces is about assumptions that pretend to be truth. When you face a challenge, write down everything you assume about it. Then write the opposite of each assumption. Ask how you would make the opposite come true, and pick one to try.\n\nTheories stay unchallenged until someone proves them wrong.\n\nSlice and Dice lists the parts of an item so you can improve each one. Car makers use this tool to design new models. They list the parts of a car and study how each feature can be made better.\n\nCherry Split splits the challenge into two big pieces and treats each one on its own until a new idea hides inside one of them. Start by splitting the problem in two. Pick one side and list its features. Study each detail until you find something you can change.\n\nThink Bubbles is a mind map. It shows how the pieces of a challenge connect. A mind map gives you a picture of how your brain links information. It is easier to move things around on a map than to shuffle them in your head.\n\nScamper pushes you to ask questions until a new answer appears. If you want to be a better public speaker, Scamper can help. Ask yourself what strategy you could swap in for your current style, how you could combine your style with another, what you can borrow from a speaker you admire, how you could change your current style, how you could make parts of it stronger, what habits you need to drop, and how you could rearrange the whole thing.\n\nYou can use Scamper on almost any problem.',
        wordCount: 264
      },
      {
        title: 'Look inside for answers',
        text: 'Many answers sit just below the surface of the mind. To bring them up, try these intuitive tools. Chilling Out, Blue Roses, The Three Bs, Rattlesnakes and Roses, and Stone Soup.\n\nChilling Out relaxes the mind and body until you slip into a deep, calm state. In that mode, ideas buried in your subconscious rise to the surface.\n\nBlue Roses is about intuition. Intuition means listening to how you feel about a situation and using that feeling to choose your next move.\n\nYou can train your intuition by making quick guesses about everyday life.\n\nWhen your phone rings, try to guess who is calling. Use your intuitive skills whenever it makes sense, and combine them when you can.\n\nThe Three Bs stand for bus, bed, and bath. This tool uses the power of incubation. Ideas show up when you are not trying. Instead of staring at the problem, do something else. While your mind is busy elsewhere, a strong idea can rise on its own. Get clear on the problem, gather the facts, let your brain register the need to solve it, walk away for a set amount of time, and when you return, you may find the answer waiting.\n\nRattlesnakes and Roses plays with the flow of ideas. New ideas come from comparing things from very different fields and finding the bridges between them. Pick a keyword from the problem you want to solve, pick an unrelated field you know something about, list the images you associate with that field, and look for ties between your keyword and that list.\n\nOur imagination is one of the things that sets us apart from every other creature.\n\nStone Soup is the what if tool. In this mode, do not judge any idea that comes up. Just ask what the world would look like if the idea were true. Big leaps of imagination can lead to fresh answers for old problems.',
        wordCount: 280
      },
      {
        title: 'Final thoughts',
        text: 'The human mind holds a treasury of ideas that can change the world. Anyone can think like a creative genius under the right conditions. The trouble is that most of us have been trained to think in narrow, familiar ways, and that habit buries our originality deep in the subconscious. The thinkertoys dive into that sea of ideas and bring them up into the light.\n\nThe tools come in two flavors. Linear thinkertoys help you improve a concept or theory that already exists. Intuitive thinkertoys help you create value where none existed before. Used together, the tools wake up both the analytical and the creative sides of the brain.\n\nDo not assume the best idea cannot be made better. Progress depends on people who keep inventing and reinventing. You have to feel a steady itch with the best plan in front of you in order to build something better.\n\nThere are no good or bad events in themselves. Events take on the meaning we give them. Train your mind to read events from many angles and never lock yourself into a single view. Once your mind can see many possibilities, you will not be shaken by passing trouble.\n\nIf you want to become a solver, switch your self image from a kitten to a monkey through daily affirmations. Learn the tools in this summary and put them to work.\n\nTry this. The first move toward a creative mind is to take on your fears, uncertainties, and doubts. Use the tick tock exercise. Draw a table with two columns. Label one tick and the other tock. Under tick, write down the negative thought, fear, or doubt. Look at it carefully. Under tock, write the positive version of that thought.\n\nYou made it to the end. Well done.',
        wordCount: 282
      }
    ]
  },

  'this-is-how-they-tell-me-the-world-ends.json': {
    base: { id: 'this-is-how-they-tell-me-the-world-ends', title: 'This Is How They Tell Me the World Ends', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781607642277 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'A new normal in the connected world',
        text: 'Ukraine declared independence from the Soviet Union through a referendum, but many people have long suspected outside hands in the blackouts that hit Ukrainian cities.\n\nThe attack knocked out railways, ATMs, gas stations, the postal service, and the radiation monitors at the Chornobyl nuclear site. It all started after Ukraine rose up against the Russian government in 2014. Viktor Yanukovych, then the president, was pushed out of office and plans moved forward to elect a Western leaning leader. The vote was hit by glitches that looked like Russian fingerprints.\n\nA cyberattack can take down anything that runs on a network.\n\nNo paper trail ties the Kremlin to hackers waging cyberwar against Ukraine, the United States, and other rivals, but the body language of President Putin gave those freelancers cover. In a striking twist, Putin praised Russian hackers as patriotic citizens and promised to call on them when needed.\n\nCyberattacks from China, the United States, Russia, and North Korea point to a new shape of war. America intelligence chiefs have found real threats aimed at the power grid, online retail, and other digital assets. The worry in the United States has two roots. Ukraine has only a thin slice of its economy online, and Russia still managed to freeze Kyiv. Imagine what would happen to a country that runs on the internet if it took a hit like that.\n\nThis summary will walk you through a cast of characters and a set of stories about how different groups race to grab and hold the internet. You will get an unusual look at the people who shape the web.',
        wordCount: 257
      },
      {
        title: 'A journey into the cave of secrets',
        text: 'Burned out from writing about cybersecurity for the Times, reporter Nicole Perlroth took a break in Kenya. She spent time in rural parts of the country, away from her laptop.\n\nThree weeks into the trip, she drove back to Nairobi, where the cell signal was strong, and checked her phone. As expected, the inbox was full. One message jumped out. Her editor at the Times needed her back urgently.\n\nOnce she was back, the new assignment was to work with the Guardian and ProPublica on two stories built on the Snowden leaks.\n\nEdward Snowden, a former contractor for the National Security Agency, leaked documents that showed how wide NSA surveillance had grown.\n\nThe two stories Perlroth helped write were about what the NSA could do and how well spy agencies broke digital codes.\n\nIn her reporting, Perlroth learned that the NSA often pulled data through back channels, hacking the inside servers of big tech firms like Yahoo. Back channeling, in the cybersecurity world, means passing information through hidden routes that attackers or defenders set up.\n\nHackers find back channels by spotting software flaws. These flaws are called zero days because the software maker has had no time to fix them before they are used.\n\nBoth criminals and defenders hunt for zero days, and the hunt has fueled many attacks. Chinese hackers, for example, stole some of the most guarded source code in Silicon Valley by riding these flaws.\n\nBack to the NSA story. Perlroth and her team realized the copy of the Snowden documents they had was not enough to write the full picture, so they kept digging.\n\nAfter months of working alone, for safety, the team was dismayed to find they had been used. The British side published their own stories without crediting Perlroth or anyone else on the Times team. The Guardian had wanted the Times team along as cover against British intelligence, not as partners.',
        wordCount: 268
      },
      {
        title: 'Lone players with global reach',
        text: 'Almost everyone Perlroth talked to at the start of her reporting on the zero day market told her it was a wild goose chase. Even governments were not in charge of zero days. They were just one set of buyers among many. That meant a government had no reason to spill its zero day secrets to a reporter. Perlroth pressed on. She had a knack for the work and found a few zero day traders.\n\nOne key contact was John P. Watters, a businessman with a sharp eye. During the dot com bust around 1999, Watters picked up a struggling cybersecurity firm called iDefense for a tiny sum. Yes, ten dollars. With the small staff left in place, including two young hackers named David Endler and Sunil James, Watters tried to turn the company around.\n\nThe plan the two hackers pitched was simple. Pay outside hackers for zero day finds, then warn iDefense clients before the software maker shipped a patch. The plan was a gamble, but the bet paid off. After running the firm for three years, Watters sold iDefense to VeriSign for forty million dollars.\n\nKeep good people on staff and give them room to share ideas.\n\nPerlroth also met a middleman she called Jimmy Sabien. Sabien was not a company builder, but he brokered deals between governments and hackers, and between security firms and the people who wanted bugs kept quiet.\n\nThe old rule about an eye for an eye leaves everyone blind.\n\nAnother contact was Charlie Miller, one of the NSA top talent for breaking into networks through bugs and zero days. Miller later went public with what he knew about the cyber arms market, much like Snowden did, but Miller stayed within the rules.\n\nThrough these and other sources, Perlroth gathered the material that would shape her reporting on cybersecurity.',
        wordCount: 263
      },
      {
        title: 'A short history of cyber spying',
        text: 'The use of zero days goes back further than the internet. During the Cold War, the United States worked hard to figure out how the Soviet KGB was pulling diplomatic secrets out of the US embassy in Moscow. The puzzle was that the embassy scrambled every message that left the building. The answer turned out to be hiding in the electric typewriters used by staff. One theory held that a Soviet mole had planted the bug while the typewriters passed through Russian customs. The NSA never proved which theory was right.\n\nThe bug let the Soviets read every keystroke and grab messages before they were scrambled.\n\nData scrambling and cyber spying both predate the internet. The web gave the work a much wider reach.\n\nPlanting code inside another country technology is a routine part of the spy game. There is no law against it. The best a country can do is defend its own systems.\n\nThe lack of rules does not mean governments admit to spying on each other. Espionage runs on deniability. Officials can always claim they knew nothing.\n\nOrganizations cannot stop the world from changing. The smart ones change before they have to.\n\nThe United States and Iran offer a clear modern case. In 2008, President George W. Bush signed off on what became the first cyber weapon of mass destruction, a worm known as Olympic Games. The worm slipped into Iran Natanz nuclear plant even though the plant was off the public internet. Within a year, the worm had wrecked two thousand uranium enriching centrifuges. The final payload made the centrifuges spin out of control and wrecked the system.',
        wordCount: 256
      },
      {
        title: 'What big cyber wars mean for everyone',
        text: 'In December 2009, a serious attack hit Google network. People call it the Aurora attack. Before Google realized it was under fire, US intelligence was already looking at hackers who were hitting companies tied to defense work. The trail led back to senior officials in China.\n\nThe two names that came up were Zhou Yongkang, who handled security, and Li Changchun, a powerful figure in charge of propaganda. Secret files showed that the US believed Changchun had been angered by what he read about himself online, and that anger was a likely motive for the attacks.\n\nThe Google hack was a big moment. It showed that countries use cyber attacks to fight each other and to shape what people see online. That is a new kind of war, one that runs on computers and networks rather than bullets and tanks. The fear in that picture is that any company, even a giant like Google, can be a target.\n\nAurora also showed that these online fights are about more than theft or spying. They are about controlling what people read and believe. When a government does not like what is online, it may try to rewrite or hide it. That is a serious problem for free speech and for the way people gather information.\n\nThis kind of warfare touches everyone, not only governments or big companies.\n\nThe Google story is a warning. It reminds us to protect our computers and our information. We have to stay alert to the countries and hackers who may try to attack us or shape what we see online.\n\nGood computer security and a clear view of what is happening in cyber warfare matter to everyone. Cyber attacks are real, and they can hit anyone who uses the internet.\n\nA small note worth knowing. The people behind the WannaCry ransomware used a tool called EternalBlue, which they had stolen from the NSA.',
        wordCount: 291
      },
      {
        title: 'A cycle of grudges and revenge',
        text: 'Tensions and payback have been building for years between the big powers online. The fight is not only about viruses and hacks. It is rooted in politics and national interest. Countries now use their cyber talent for both defense and offense, building a new kind of war that is quiet but can be devastating. The United States, Russia, and China are locked in a struggle that uses code and digital tricks to spy, steal, and disrupt.\n\nThe United States has long led this digital fight, watching rivals and guarding its own secrets. Other countries are catching up. Russia and China have hacker teams that break into US systems, steal data, and sometimes just stir up trouble to show they can.\n\nIn 2016, during the US elections, Russian hackers broke into email systems, stole messages, and leaked them. The goal was not to pick a winner. It was to shake trust in the system.\n\nThe fight is not only between countries. Hackers play a big role too. Some work for cash, selling their skills to the highest bidder. Some go after companies or governments they dislike. Some simply enjoy the thrill of breaking into a system no one else can.\n\nThis new war is different. It is silent and hidden. You may not know a battle is on until it ends. A power plant goes dark. A bank systems freeze. A government website goes offline. Behind it all, someone somewhere is typing on a keyboard.\n\nThe dangers are real. Hospitals lose access to patient records. Banks lose millions. Governments grind to a halt. The scariest part is that we may not know who is behind the attack. Was it a country, a group, or one person? In this shadowy world, it is hard to tell.\n\nCybersecurity teams push back. They hunt for weaknesses before the bad actors do, and they build digital walls and traps to guard our information.\n\nHacking is a game of cat and mouse. Attackers find a way in, and defenders close the gap.\n\nThis online world is our new reality. We live online, so the fight over this space touches everyone. It is not only about governments and secrets. It is about our personal data, our money, and our safety.',
        wordCount: 311
      },
      {
        title: 'Closing thoughts',
        text: 'For years, intelligence agencies hid digital flaws in the name of tracking rivals, planning for war, and protecting national security. That line is wearing thin. The internet has tied us all together in ways we cannot undo, and a flaw that hits one corner of the world can hit all of us. The wall between the physical and the digital is breaking down.\n\nThe United States is one of the biggest players in the zero day market, and it has serious financial weight. A new rule that required every zero day dealer or hacker to hand over their tools for patching would shift the norm. It would also discourage dealers from selling the same tools to foreign governments that could use them against the United States, and it would tighten security for everyone.\n\nCountries like the United States need clearer rules. For example, requiring hackers and dealers to share their tools for patching could set a new standard. It would guard against the misuse of those tools and lift the overall level of cybersecurity. The rules would also shape how hackers, brokers, and defense contractors share information with foreign governments. The goal is balance, so that defenders can still talk and act across borders when threats pop up.\n\nTry this. The internet is full of traps, so it pays to be careful about where you click. A few habits help. Keep your privacy settings on. Watch what you download, and avoid strange pop ups. Pick strong passwords. Buy only from secure retail sites. And think about what you post, because it can attract attention you did not bargain for.\n\nYou made it to the end. Nice work.',
        wordCount: 246
      }
    ]
  }
};
